[Method]
StoreImage
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method is used to store what has been drawn or printed to the PictureBox’s paintable area to memory.  What this does is makes all lines, arcs, text, etc. become part of the stored picture that the PictureBox uses to paint from.  This method must be called after all objects have been drawn to the PictureBox, or possible errors could occur, especially if another dialog box is moved of the PictureBox and what has been drawn will be erased.
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName


[Method]
GetPictureSize
[Prefix]
Odcl_
[Desc]
This method will return the size of a picture, indicated by its Id.
[Arguments Return] as List
ProjectName
\par\tab PictureID
[as Integer]



[Method]
Clear
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method clears the control, including any pictures set using the Picture property.
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName

[Method]
Refresh
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method repaints the PictureBox using the image last stored by Odcl_PictureBox_StoreImage.  Any pictures set using the Picture property or Odcl_PictureBox_LoadPicture  will not be removed. 
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName

[Method]
DrawLine
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method draws a list of lines in the control.
\par \par \b Note:\b0 \par Create list in the manor shown as follows: \par 
          (List (List x y ...) (List x y ...) ...)
\par We have found ObjectARX does not always like lists created as follows:
\par          '(x y ...) (x y ...) ... 
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName
\par\tab 
[Begin List]
[Begin List]
\par\tab StartX
[as Integer]
\par\tab StartY
[as Integer]
\par\tab EndX
[as Integer]
\par\tab EndY
[as Integer]
\par\tab LineColor
[as Integer]
[End List]
\par\tab ...
[End List]



[Method]
DrawArc
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method draws an arc on the control. This method requires center coordinates, a radius, and start and end points to calculate the start and end angles of the arc. These points don’t need to fall directly on the arc, they are used to calculate the start and end angles.
\par \par \b Note:\b0 \par Create list in the manor shown as follows: \par 
          (List (List x y ...) (List x y ...) ...)
\par We have found ObjectARX does not always like lists created as follows:
\par          '(x y ...) (x y ...) ... 
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName
\par\tab
[Begin List]
[Begin List]
\par\tab UpperLeftX
[as Integer]
\par\tab UpperLeftY
[as Integer]
\par\tab Width
[as Integer]
\par\tab Height
[as Integer]
\par\tab StartAngleX
[as Integer]
\par\tab StartAngleY
[as Integer]
\par\tab EndAngleX
[as Integer]
\par\tab EndAngleY
[as Integer]
\par\tab Color
[as Integer]
[End List]
\par\tab ...
[End List]



[Method]
DrawCircle
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method draws a circle on the control. A rectangle is used because it allows both circles and ellipses to be drawn using the same method.
