[Method]
DrawWrappedText
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method draws text on the control. If the text is going to be drawn outside the allowable width area the text is automatically wrapped around to the next line or lines. A bounding rectangle is used to define where the text is to be drawn.
\par If a 0 or -27 is passed into BackColor, then the text is draw transparently.
\par \par \b Note:\b0
\par \pard\fi-310\li310 1.\tab The height parameter is automatically calculated and returned with the method. If the BackColor argument is not passed the PictureBox’s BackColor property is used.
\par \pard\fi-310\li310 2.\tab Create list in the manor shown as follows:
\par \tab \tab (List (List x y ...) (List x y ...) ...)
\par \pard\fi-310\li310 \tab We have found ObjectARX does not always like lists created as follows:
\par \tab \tab '(x y ...) (x y ...) ... 
\par \pard\fi-0\li0  
[Arguments Return] as Integer
ProjectFileName
\par\tab 
[Begin List]
[Begin List]
\par\tab UpperLeftX
[as Integer]
\par\tab UpperLeftY
[as Integer]
\par\tab Width
[as Integer]
\par\tab ForeColor
[as Integer]
\par\tab \i[Optional] \i0 BackColor 
[as Integer]
\par\tab Text
[as String]
\par\tab Justification
[as String: L = Left, C = Center, R = Right]
[End List]
\par\tab ...
[End List]



[Method]
DrawText
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method draws text on the control. If the BackColor argument is not passed the PictureBox’s BackColor property is used. 
\par If a 0 or -27 is passed into BackColor, then the text is draw transparently.
\par \par \b Justification \b0
\par \pard\fi-410\li410 TL \tab Top Left	
\par \pard\fi-410\li410 TC \tab Top Center	
\par \pard\fi-410\li410 TR \tab Top Right	
\par \pard\fi-410\li410 BL \tab Bottom Left	
\par \pard\fi-410\li410 BC \tab Bottom Center	
\par \pard\fi-410\li410 BR \tab Bottom Right	
\par \pard\fi-0\li0 \par \b Note:\b0 \par Create list in the manor shown as follows: \par 
          (List (List x y ...) (List x y ...) ...)
\par We have found ObjectARX does not always like lists created as follows:
\par          '(x y ...) (x y ...) ... 
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName
\par\tab 
[Begin List]
[Begin List]
\par\tab UpperLeftX
[as Integer]
\par\tab UpperLeftY
[as Integer]
\par\tab Width
[as Integer]
\par\tab ForeColor
[as Integer]
\par\tab \i[Optional] \i0 BackColor 
[as Integer]
\par\tab Text
[as String]
\par\tab Justification
[as String]
\par\tab \i[Optional] \i0 Disabled
[as Integer: 1, or T = Disabled, 0 or Nil = Enabled]
[End List]
\par\tab ...
[End List]



[Method]
GetTextExtent
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method will return the height and width of the text passed in for calculation.
[Arguments Return] as List (Width Height)
ProjectFileName
\par\tab Text
[as String]


[Method]
PaintPicture
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method will paint a picture anywhere on the control. The dialog box must be visible. If you intend to use this method to show a picture of pictures on the the PictureBox, make this call from the OnPaint event of the PictureBox so that the image is shown at the correct time.
\par \par \b Note:\b0 \par Create list in the manor shown as follows: \par 
          (List (List x y ...) (List x y ...) ...)
\par We have found ObjectARX does not always like lists created as follows:
\par          '(x y ...) (x y ...) ... 
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName
\par\tab 
[Begin List]
[Begin List]
\par\tab UpperLeftX
[as Integer]
\par\tab UpperLeftY
[as Integer]
\par\tab PictureID
[as Integer]
\par\tab \i[Optional] \i0 Enabled
[as Integer: 1, or T = Disabled, 0 or Nil = Enabled]
\par\tab \i[Optional] \i0 UseMask
[as Integer: 1, or T = Use, 0 or Nil = Don't Use]
[End List]
\par\tab ...
[End List]


[Method]
LoadPictureFile
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method will load a picture file of type .bmp, .ico, .jpg, and .wmf, into the PictureBox control.
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName
\par\tab FileName
[as String]



[Method]
DrawPoint
[Prefix]
Odcl_PictureBox_
[Desc]
This method will paint a single point on the control any specified color. Note: this method does not accept lists passed in to specify a group of points to be drawn.  Due to ObjectARX limitations in lists, at this time, small lists cannot be supported.
[Arguments]
ProjectFileName
\par\tab nX
[as Integer]
\par\tab nY
[as Integer]
\par\tab Color
[as Integer]


[End of File]